2
00:04:33,938 --> 00:04:36,588
- Please.
- No fruit or vegetables.

3
00:04:36,722 --> 00:04:38,031
That includes...

4
00:04:38,161 --> 00:04:41,510
pomegranates. It's on your form.

5
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:44,104
- I like to eat the seed
of this fruit.

6
00:04:44,241 --> 00:04:47,536
One each day. For luck.

7
00:04:47,665 --> 00:04:49,966
- I'm sorry, that's not allowed.

8
00:04:50,096 --> 00:04:53,293
[Announcement]: For security
reasons, please do not leave

9
00:04:53,424 --> 00:04:56,587
your bags unattended.
Veuillez garder avec vous

10
00:04:56,720 --> 00:04:58,727
vos bagages a main
en tout temps

11
00:04:58,863 --> 00:05:00,204
pour des raisons de securite

12
00:05:00,334 --> 00:05:02,090
- What are you doing?

13
00:05:02,223 --> 00:05:04,427
- This way, I don't need
to bring it in.

14
00:05:04,559 --> 00:05:09,479
I eat it here,
at the gate of your country.

15
00:05:11,182 --> 00:05:12,522
Look.

16
00:05:17,197 --> 00:05:21,157
So, I bring luck in my stomach.

17
00:05:21,292 --> 00:05:23,561
Will you try it?

18
00:05:34,763 --> 00:05:39,880
Raffi, the real point of this poem
is that the girlfriend is crazy!

19
00:05:43,434 --> 00:05:47,689
'No!' The girlfriend said angrily,
'I want your mother's heart!'

20
00:05:52,137 --> 00:05:54,592
So the boy went and killed his mother.

21
00:05:54,697 --> 00:05:56,103
You know what they say...

22
00:05:56,232 --> 00:05:58,207
There's always
a woman at the heart of it.

23
00:05:58,792 --> 00:06:01,378
As he ran through the streets
with her heart in his hands,

24
00:06:01,512 --> 00:06:03,170
he tripped and fell.

25
00:06:03,752 --> 00:06:07,396
His mother's heart cried out...

26
00:06:09,511 --> 00:06:11,966
'My poor boy!'

27
00:06:12,359 --> 00:06:15,075
'Did you hurt yourself?'

28
00:06:32,005 --> 00:06:33,313
- You know what?

29
00:06:33,444 --> 00:06:34,753
I completely forgot
you had a party.

30
00:06:34,884 --> 00:06:37,056
- I told you she...
The party's not the point.

31
00:06:37,188 --> 00:06:39,292
The fact is, you make
these physical appearances

32
00:06:39,428 --> 00:06:40,737
without letting anybody know.

33
00:06:40,867 --> 00:06:42,809
I mean, it makes
perfect sense to me.

34
00:06:42,947 --> 00:06:44,954
- Why would I need
to tell anyone?

35
00:06:45,091 --> 00:06:46,814
- I'm not saying
you need permission.

36
00:06:47,011 --> 00:06:48,953
Permission for what?

37
00:06:49,442 --> 00:06:51,329
- Celia, just try to understand
her point of view.

38
00:06:51,394 --> 00:06:53,304
Raffi, stop talking about your mother.

39
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:22,621
Why can't I read her book?

40
00:07:26,526 --> 00:07:29,144
- Just wait till it comes out.

41
00:07:29,278 --> 00:07:30,620
- But you've read it.

42
00:07:34,909 --> 00:07:37,276
- Give me your copy.
- No.

43
00:07:37,405 --> 00:07:39,380
- Why not?

44
00:07:39,517 --> 00:07:43,161
I'm part of the family.
- Look, I promised her that I...

45
00:07:43,293 --> 00:07:46,554
- What?
- I wouldn't give you my copy.

46
00:07:51,804 --> 00:07:54,192
- Please.
- Celia, come on.

47
00:07:57,851 --> 00:08:01,145
- I'm making it hard for you
to be the perfect son.

48
00:08:01,275 --> 00:08:02,835
I'm sorry.

49
00:08:02,970 --> 00:08:05,271
- I don't get why
it has to be this way.

50
00:08:06,905 --> 00:08:08,400
- Yes, you do.

51
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:12,627
- I was happier
when you got along.

52
00:08:14,777 --> 00:08:17,231
- It wasn't as much fun.
- Says who?

53
00:08:21,304 --> 00:08:25,875
- The ghost of the father...
my father, not yours.

54
00:08:26,008 --> 00:08:28,855
Yours died like a hero.

55
00:08:28,984 --> 00:08:31,700
Mine died in a stupid accident,
according to her.

56
00:08:36,278 --> 00:08:39,955
You look after your goals,
Raffi. And l'II look after mine.

57
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:28,328
- Did you give her my book?

58
00:09:30,608 --> 00:09:32,266
- This is too weird for me.

59
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:34,375
- What is weird, Raffi?

60
00:09:37,743 --> 00:09:40,743
Smoking pot? Or sleeping
with your step-sister?

61
00:09:40,879 --> 00:09:44,359
- I'm old enough to know what...
- What are you telling me, Raffi?

62
00:09:44,494 --> 00:09:46,534
That this is all normal?

63
00:09:46,670 --> 00:09:50,182
That she should continue
to harass me?

64
00:09:50,318 --> 00:09:53,384
Tell people that l'm responsible
for her father's death?

65
00:09:56,205 --> 00:09:59,272
No one asked her to come here.
She could've stayed in Montreal.

66
00:09:59,405 --> 00:10:00,714
- She needed us.

67
00:10:00,845 --> 00:10:03,562
- What she needs is to destroy me
the same way

68
00:10:03,692 --> 00:10:05,252
she thinks I destroyed him.

69
00:10:05,389 --> 00:10:07,756
- Mom...
- She will never understand

70
00:10:07,885 --> 00:10:10,251
why I stopped loving her father's.

71
00:10:10,380 --> 00:10:12,551
- Or for seeing someone else?

72
00:10:12,684 --> 00:10:14,789
- I'm not accountable to her.

73
00:10:16,971 --> 00:10:18,313
- I am.

74
00:10:20,108 --> 00:10:21,416
- Why?

75
00:10:21,546 --> 00:10:23,968
- Because I love her.

76
00:10:24,522 --> 00:10:26,410
That's a new twist to the story.

77
00:10:28,266 --> 00:10:30,687
Why do you need to call it a story?

78
00:10:31,242 --> 00:10:34,470
Don't you have anything better to do
at your age than fall in love?

79
00:10:34,825 --> 00:10:38,687
My age? You were married at my age!

80
00:11:05,957 --> 00:11:10,332
- Thank you.
- Tony, why don't you say grace.

81
00:11:10,469 --> 00:11:14,047
- For what we are about
to receive, may the Lord

82
00:11:14,181 --> 00:11:16,962
make us truly grateful. Amen.
- Amen.

83
00:11:18,500 --> 00:11:19,810
- Dad?

84
00:11:19,940 --> 00:11:21,402
- Yes.

85
00:11:23,556 --> 00:11:25,596
- Why didn't you say 'Amen'?

86
00:11:30,179 --> 00:11:32,284
- Well, I say it inside.

87
00:11:32,419 --> 00:11:34,174
- Inside where?

88
00:11:36,770 --> 00:11:39,640
- Inside my head.

89
00:11:39,779 --> 00:11:42,495
- Can God hear it
inside your head?

90
00:11:44,834 --> 00:11:46,328
- What do you think, Dad?

91
00:11:54,976 --> 00:11:56,667
- God hears all your thoughts.

92
00:11:58,208 --> 00:12:00,117
- But you don't believe in God.

93
00:12:12,126 --> 00:12:14,297
Grandpa, that's not really
what happened.

94
00:12:14,942 --> 00:12:16,950
- See you.
- Bye, Grandpa.

95
00:12:41,627 --> 00:12:43,699
- Here's the situation, Dad.

96
00:12:45,978 --> 00:12:48,018
Whenever Tony comes over alone,
he's fine.

97
00:12:50,361 --> 00:12:52,500
We play, he laughs,
he's full of joy.

98
00:12:54,201 --> 00:12:56,721
Whenever you're around,
he becomes quiet and withdrawn.

99
00:12:56,857 --> 00:12:59,224
- That isn't true, Philip.
- And we can't stand it.

100
00:13:01,272 --> 00:13:02,963
The more oppression you...

101
00:13:03,096 --> 00:13:05,038
- Oppression?

102
00:13:05,176 --> 00:13:08,787
He loves when l'm there.

103
00:13:08,919 --> 00:13:11,025
- The more you bring this heavy
cloud into our apartment,

104
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:13,428
the more he believes
that the way we live is wrong.

105
00:13:13,559 --> 00:13:14,900
- Now, I have never
told him that.

106
00:13:15,031 --> 00:13:16,973
- You don't need to.
He can feel your disgust.

107
00:13:17,111 --> 00:13:18,802
- Philip...

108
00:13:18,934 --> 00:13:23,342
- And where did he get that...
Ali doesn't believe in God?

109
00:13:23,478 --> 00:13:27,601
- He asked me why your friend
doesn't say grace with us...

110
00:13:27,734 --> 00:13:32,654
- My friend.
- I told him he had his own God.

111
00:13:32,789 --> 00:13:34,447
And that's true.

112
00:13:36,405 --> 00:13:37,997
Philip, l'm...

113
00:13:38,132 --> 00:13:43,499
l'm trying really hard to...
accept all this. I really am.

114
00:13:43,635 --> 00:13:45,708
- Dad...

115
00:13:48,788 --> 00:13:51,634
you're retiring soon.

116
00:13:51,763 --> 00:13:54,610
You're gonna have a lot
of time on your hands.

117
00:13:54,739 --> 00:13:59,310
Either you make an effort
to change your attitude,

118
00:13:59,442 --> 00:14:05,071
or you're not... welcome
at our place anymore.

119
00:14:26,606 --> 00:14:28,167
- Where you coming from?

120
00:14:28,303 --> 00:14:29,732
- Turkey.

121
00:14:31,502 --> 00:14:33,159
- Can you open this?

122
00:14:46,989 --> 00:14:48,515
What are these?

123
00:14:48,653 --> 00:14:50,758
- It's film.
It's motion-picture film.

124
00:14:50,893 --> 00:14:52,802
It's for a movie.

125
00:14:52,940 --> 00:14:54,434
I have, uh...

126
00:15:02,060 --> 00:15:05,288
- This sort of thing is usually
done through a bonder.

127
00:15:05,418 --> 00:15:07,458
- Well, they wanted me
to hand-deliver it.

128
00:15:07,594 --> 00:15:09,928
- Who's 'they'?

129
00:15:10,057 --> 00:15:12,327
- It's very valuable footage.

130
00:15:12,458 --> 00:15:15,393
- Can you open it?
- Well, no.

131
00:15:15,530 --> 00:15:18,398
It's exposed film.
It'II destroy it.

132
00:15:18,537 --> 00:15:20,391
- Oh?

133
00:15:20,521 --> 00:15:22,822
- It's for a movie that's
being shot here in Canada.

134
00:15:22,952 --> 00:15:25,221
I had to go to Turkey
to get some process shots.

135
00:15:25,353 --> 00:15:27,938
- Process shots?
- Shots that'II be used

136
00:15:28,073 --> 00:15:30,341
for digital effects. And plates.
That sort of thing.

137
00:15:30,471 --> 00:15:32,992
- I don't understand.

138
00:15:33,128 --> 00:15:35,298
- There needs to be scenes
of hundreds of people

139
00:15:35,431 --> 00:15:37,536
passing through these places.

140
00:15:37,671 --> 00:15:39,613
And it's too expensive
to take actors and extras

141
00:15:39,751 --> 00:15:43,133
to the middle of nowhere, so we
shoot empty shots of locations.

142
00:15:43,270 --> 00:15:45,158
It's cheaper
to add people in later on.

143
00:15:45,286 --> 00:15:46,627
- Huh.

144
00:15:58,085 --> 00:15:59,645
L'II be back.

145
00:16:39,104 --> 00:16:44,319
Arshile Gorky's Studio
New York City, 1934

146
00:18:06,711 --> 00:18:09,874
- Arshile Gorky remains one
of the most influential figures

147
00:18:10,005 --> 00:18:12,656
in modern art.

148
00:18:12,789 --> 00:18:14,960
His most famous painting,
'The Artist and His Mother,'

149
00:18:15,093 --> 00:18:18,127
is based on a photograph
that was taken in 1912;

150
00:18:18,261 --> 00:18:21,326
the only image that exists
of the artist's early life

151
00:18:21,460 --> 00:18:23,435
in his native land.

152
00:18:25,140 --> 00:18:27,889
Gorky is seen holding
a bunch of small flowers

153
00:18:28,020 --> 00:18:30,387
as a fragrant gift
to his absent father,

154
00:18:30,515 --> 00:18:33,362
the intended recipient
of this remarkable photograph.

155
00:18:35,570 --> 00:18:36,880
- I'm confused.

156
00:18:37,011 --> 00:18:39,050
Had Gorky changed his name
by this point?

157
00:18:39,186 --> 00:18:40,495
- No.

158
00:18:40,626 --> 00:18:42,251
He changed it in his twenties,

159
00:18:42,387 --> 00:18:44,492
after his arrival
to the United States.

160
00:18:44,626 --> 00:18:46,927
- Celia, sit down.

161
00:18:47,057 --> 00:18:49,392
- Gorky looks prematurely solemn.

162
00:18:49,521 --> 00:18:52,041
With almond eyes and oval face,

163
00:18:52,177 --> 00:18:54,697
his hair combed neatly
to the side,

164
00:18:54,833 --> 00:18:57,647
Shushan looks bravely
at the camera,

165
00:18:57,776 --> 00:19:00,460
challenging her absent husband...
- Challenging?

166
00:19:00,592 --> 00:19:02,283
Why would you say that?

167
00:19:02,416 --> 00:19:03,724
Isn't it obvious he knew

168
00:19:03,856 --> 00:19:07,205
the Armenians were about to be
massacred? He went to America

169
00:19:07,344 --> 00:19:09,002
to prepare a life
for his family.

170
00:19:09,135 --> 00:19:10,760
They wanted to send him
a photograph

171
00:19:10,894 --> 00:19:12,203
to let him know
they're still alive.

172
00:19:12,335 --> 00:19:14,757
There's nothing challenging...
- Gorky never understood

173
00:19:14,895 --> 00:19:16,999
why his father did not return.

174
00:19:17,134 --> 00:19:19,556
- Celia, just sit down. Come on.

175
00:19:19,694 --> 00:19:23,555
- Aren't you confusing Gorky's
father with your dead husband?

176
00:19:23,693 --> 00:19:25,962
I mean, your first dead husband.

177
00:19:26,093 --> 00:19:30,631
The one who was shot
by the police. The terrorist.

178
00:19:30,765 --> 00:19:32,106
- Sit down.

179
00:19:32,237 --> 00:19:35,552
Sit down. We're here
to listen to this lecture.

180
00:19:35,691 --> 00:19:37,350
- Let's go.

181
00:19:53,002 --> 00:19:56,831
- 'The Artist and His Mother'
is not simply a painted version

182
00:19:56,970 --> 00:19:58,344
of a photograph.

183
00:19:58,473 --> 00:20:01,789
The differences underline
the expressive elements

184
00:20:01,929 --> 00:20:04,034
that make this piece
such a powerful

185
00:20:04,169 --> 00:20:05,794
work of art.

186
00:20:09,608 --> 00:20:15,620
Gorky's homage to his mother was
bound to take on sacred quality.

187
00:20:17,863 --> 00:20:21,792
His experience as a survivor
of the Armenian genocide

188
00:20:21,927 --> 00:20:24,643
is at the root
of its spiritual power.

189
00:20:26,726 --> 00:20:32,868
With this painting, Gorky had
saved his mother from oblivion,

190
00:20:32,998 --> 00:20:36,771
snatching her
out of a pile of corpses

191
00:20:36,901 --> 00:20:39,519
to place her
on a pedestal of life.

192
00:21:10,785 --> 00:21:13,054
Let me look at you son.

193
00:21:13,569 --> 00:21:14,998
You're missing a button!

194
00:21:15,137 --> 00:21:17,820
It must have fallen off...

195
00:21:17,953 --> 00:21:20,537
Hold your hand in front of it.

196
00:21:20,672 --> 00:21:21,620
Like this?

197
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:22,709
Yes.

198
00:22:05,915 --> 00:22:08,631
I'm just so shocked
to see you here.

199
00:22:08,763 --> 00:22:10,105
I've seen all your films
and I really...

200
00:22:11,323 --> 00:22:12,632
- Please. Please.

201
00:22:12,762 --> 00:22:14,616
- We're the ones
who are overwhelmed by this.

202
00:22:14,746 --> 00:22:16,655
I've been writing
this screenplay for five years,

203
00:22:16,794 --> 00:22:18,223
done as much research
as possible

204
00:22:18,362 --> 00:22:20,696
and you come up with this.
- With what?

205
00:22:20,825 --> 00:22:23,825
- Well, that Gorky was a child
during the rebellion in Van,

206
00:22:23,961 --> 00:22:25,271
that he was there.
It's amazing.

207
00:22:25,401 --> 00:22:27,986
- My mother
was a genocide survivor.

208
00:22:28,120 --> 00:22:32,942
All my life, I promised to make
a film to tell her story,

209
00:22:33,079 --> 00:22:35,600
how she suffered.

210
00:22:35,736 --> 00:22:38,736
And now,
we are making this film.

211
00:22:38,872 --> 00:22:42,068
- I'm not understanding
something.

212
00:22:42,199 --> 00:22:44,621
Is Gorky in your film?

213
00:22:44,759 --> 00:22:46,067
- Not yet.

214
00:22:46,199 --> 00:22:47,759
- As you were speaking,
we got very excited

215
00:22:47,894 --> 00:22:51,190
about the idea of working
him in. As another character.

216
00:22:51,318 --> 00:22:53,292
Well, not an entirely
new character,

217
00:22:53,429 --> 00:22:56,331
but a character
we could build on.

218
00:22:56,469 --> 00:22:59,982
See, this amazing artist
as a young kid...

219
00:23:00,117 --> 00:23:02,321
It would be great
to have you as a consultant.

220
00:23:02,453 --> 00:23:04,973
- You have her photos, a gift

221
00:23:05,108 --> 00:23:08,818
from the ashes of all
that has been destroyed.

222
00:23:08,948 --> 00:23:10,802
We can open this gift together.

223
00:23:36,528 --> 00:23:38,121
- What's going on?

224
00:23:42,544 --> 00:23:44,399
- Why did you bring up my dad?

225
00:23:47,279 --> 00:23:48,937
Well, he didn't run away.

226
00:23:49,071 --> 00:23:51,176
Okay, my mum just had to
distance herself from him.

227
00:23:51,312 --> 00:23:54,158
- Huh. To save the family.
- He wasn't a terrorist.

228
00:23:54,287 --> 00:23:56,556
- I didn't say he was.
- You said he was a terrorist.

229
00:23:56,686 --> 00:23:59,174
- Did I? Well,

230
00:23:59,309 --> 00:24:01,132
I suppose you could see it
that way.

231
00:24:01,262 --> 00:24:04,045
I mean, he was about to
assassinate a diplomat.

232
00:24:04,174 --> 00:24:07,490
- He was a freedom fighter.
Celia, there's a difference.

233
00:24:07,630 --> 00:24:11,143
- Sure, it was
a really cool way to go.

234
00:24:11,277 --> 00:24:15,106
A lot better than my dad...
jumping off a cliff.

235
00:24:15,245 --> 00:24:16,805
- Jumping.

236
00:24:16,940 --> 00:24:19,045
- He committed suicide.
- Well, that's new.

237
00:24:19,180 --> 00:24:22,279
I thought the story was my mom
pushed him off the cliff.

238
00:24:22,412 --> 00:24:24,800
- Story.

239
00:24:24,939 --> 00:24:27,689
You think l'm making up a story?

240
00:24:27,819 --> 00:24:30,753
- No, it's...
it's not what I meant.

241
00:24:47,817 --> 00:24:49,158
- Raffi, l'm saying

242
00:24:49,288 --> 00:24:52,103
that what happened
to my father matters.

243
00:24:52,233 --> 00:24:56,160
I know that no one else cares,
but it matters to me.

244
00:24:56,295 --> 00:24:58,335
- Well, then how
do I make it matter,

245
00:24:58,471 --> 00:24:59,900
what happened to my father?

246
00:25:02,150 --> 00:25:04,900
- You just do.

247
00:25:05,031 --> 00:25:06,372
- How?

248
00:25:08,230 --> 00:25:10,205
- You go there.

249
00:25:16,357 --> 00:25:18,300
And you stick it in here.

250
00:25:20,773 --> 00:25:22,529
And you listen to it beat.

251
00:25:24,069 --> 00:25:27,931
Beat all night, all day.

252
00:25:28,068 --> 00:25:30,207
That way, you never forget.

253
00:25:46,242 --> 00:25:47,868
- Mount Ararat.

